The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Wednesday, July 07, 2004  The City Diary
																																																		A constable of the Golabari Road traffic section, Howrah, was arrested on Monday on the charge of torturing his wife. According to police, Arun Kumar Banerjees wife Sipra had lodged a complaint that her husband had been torturing her for the past three years demanding money from her father. I could not take it anymore. My five-year-old son is also suffering, Sipra said. A case under Section 498 (A) of the IPC has been started against him. Police officers said they had also tried to reform the constable but failed. He has been suspended from his job and sent to jail for 14 days by the sub-divisional judicial magistrate on Monday, said Howrah superintendent of police Mihir Kumar Bhattacharya.																																																		The CID on Tuesday busted an inter-state racket in selling stolen cars from Bihar and Uttar Pradesh. Seventeen cars were recovered. The racketeers would get stolen vehicles registered at the Public Vehicles Department in the city for a price. The CID is probing the alleged connections of the gang members with PVD officials. The sleuths believe that there are several such stolen cars in the city that have been registered here.																																																		A two-day training programme on the identification and detection of drugs and narcotic substances was inaugurated at NSC Bose International Airport on Tuesday by Barun Roy, deputy inspector general, Central Industrial Security Force (CISF). Eighty CISF personnel, from the North-Eastern states, Andaman and Nicobar, and the ports of Calcutta and Haldia will be trained. Roy stressed that the main purpose of the programme was to educate the trainees about the different forms of intoxicants, their origin, the methods employed by smugglers and counter-methods to check smuggling of drugs. 																																																		Police sent the decomposed body of an unidentified man, aged about 40 years, for post-mortem to Nilratan Sircar Medical College and Hospital on Tuesday morning. The man had been shot from a close range. At around 9.45 am, local residents noticed a large plastic bag floating in Beliaghata canal. The sealed bag was retrieved, and the Narkeldanga police station was informed since the contents of the bag smelt foul. Police said the man had probably been strangled before being shot.																																																		The decomposed body of Bilta Bhuian, 55, a native of Jharkhand who stayed in the CMC staff quarters on Tiljala Road, under Kareya police station, was recovered on Tuesday. Neighbours alerted the police after scenting a foul odour emanated from behind the closed doors. Bhuians family members had left to visit relatives in Jharkhand about three months ago, and he was living alone in his quarters, police said. 																																																		A family squabble led Mithu Majhi, 24, a resident of Belgachhia Road, to hang herself from a metal beam in her bedroom at around 10.45 am on Tuesday, police said. Mithu had been married to Sanjib Majhi, who worked in Patipukur fish market, for six-and-a-half years. They had a three-and-a-half-year-old son. The couple had quarrelled over their sons fall down a staircase on Monday, and Sanjib had accused Mithu of being irresponsible. 																																																		Four contract labourers of the Calcutta Municipal Corporation were injured when a bomb exploded in a garbage dump near Kasiabagan tank, where they were working, on Tuesday morning. Local residents rushed the injured to SSKM Hospital, where Asiruddin Mandal, 40, was stated to be in a critical condition.																																																		A 26-year-old youth, who was missing for over a month, was found dead at a house in Maniruddin Lane in Sonagachhi on Tuesday. Police said Nilotpal Poddar, a resident of Raja Basanta Roy Road, was missing since June 4. Officials of Burtolla police station said according to the post-mortem report, Poddar died of cardiac arrest.To Bhalo-Basha for organising several awareness camps for rehabilitation of drug addicts
